observations.recommendation:
We recommended the Accounting Office to:

Record the on-going projects in the total amount of ₱78.4 million in the books of accounts to present fairly the Construction in Progress accounts;

Coordinate with the Engineering Office to establish a reporting mechanism on the status of on-going constructions-in-progress and completed projects to prevent delays in recognition of the same to their appropriate accounts and to recognize the same even in the event of non-availability of actual billings from contractors.

We reiterated our recommendations and the LCE agreed to instruct the Municipal Accountant to
(a) aggressively monitor and follow through the final demand letters issued to the persons responsible for the liquidation of the outstanding cash advances;
(b) continue the withholding of salaries in case of unjustified failure to do so;
(c) recommend for the filing of appropriate administrative or criminal charges, as warranted;
(d) refrain from granting additional cash advances if the previous ones remain unsettled;
(e) strengthen and implement its internal control system on the grant and liquidation of cash advances; and
(f) seek approval for the write-off of long outstanding cash advances in accordance with prescribed procedures.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to direct the:
(a) Inventory Committee to conduct a comprehensive physical count of all property of the Municipality;
(b) OIC-GSO to
(i) collaborate with other offices that may have the needed document and information on the properties of the Municipality with the aim of completing the GSO record on PPEs; and
(ii) ensure that the information required in the PCs are provided;
(c) Municipal Accountant to
(i) endeavor to provide adequate subsidiary support documents to its PPE GL balances and
(ii) prepare the necessary journal entries to account for the depreciation expense of the PPEs acquired during the current year. Furthermore, make diligent efforts to obtain the essential information required to accurately calculate the depreciation for the PPEs from previous years;
(d) Municipal Accountant and OIC-GSO to reconcile their records for PPE accounts and investigate the cause of the variances for proper disposition;
(e) Municipal Assessor and OIC-GSO to expedite the titling of the eight parcels of land in the name of the Municipal Government of Dinalungan.

Closely follow up with the Department of Health – CVCHD on the requested breakdown of the ₱217,477.10 balance to facilitate the immediate reconciliation of records and resolution of the noted discrepancy;
Establish regular coordination and communication with the source agency to monitor the status of submitted liquidation reports and ensure timely feedback or validation of fund utilization;
Conduct periodic reconciliation of the Due to National Government Agencies account, particularly for inter-agency fund transfers, to ensure that balances reported in the financial statements are accurate, updated, and supported by verified documentation; and
Review and strengthen internal procedures for monitoring fund utilization and liquidation submissions, including proper documentation, timely reporting, and clear accountability measures.

Implement consistent enforcement of the 5 percent penalty interest and consider terminating leases for tenants with prolonged non-payment in accordance with the contract terms;
Consistently remind tenants to submit a written notice when vacating their stalls to ensure timely record updates and prevent unnecessary billing;
Regularly review and reconcile outstanding balances to identify tenants who have vacated and adjust records accordingly; and
Explore other collection measures such as issuing final demand letters, coordinating with legal counsel for persistent delinquencies and/or offering incentives for prompt payments.

Further, we recommended that instead of solely relying on reports, the Accounting to conduct periodic site visits to verify the actual number of existing tenants, ensuring the accuracy of billing records and preventing the inclusion of vacated stalls in the receivables.

Direct the LDRRMO to continuously monitor the implementation of PPAs to facilitate the timely completion thereof;
Ensure that PPAs funded out of the DRRM funds are well-planned and meticulously reviewed by the LDRRMC; and
Instruct the LDRRMO to prepare the LDRRMFIP as prescribed in COA Circular 2012-002 dated September 12, 2012 for the current year. Additionally, in a separate section, include the list of projects and activities to be funded from the unexpended LDRRMF in previous years under the Special Trust Fund.

We recommended and the LCE agreed through the:
(a) MGSO and Inventory Committee to conduct a complete physical inventory count and reconcile its result with both accounting and property records;
(b) MGSO to submit the list of unserviceable properties in the IIRUP, and henceforth facilitate its disposal in accordance with prescribed procedures;
(c) MGSO and the Municipal Treasurer, in coordination with the Municipal Budget Officer, to endeavor to register and provide insurance coverage for the Municipality’s motor vehicles prioritizing those that are in active use; and
(d) BAC to reconsider the inclusion of insurance and registration in the ABC to lessen the processing time and delay in the registration of motor vehicles.

